### Iterators

Iterators provide a uniform way to traverse elements in containers (vectors, maps, sets, etc.) regardless of the underlying data structure.

---

### Iterator Types

| Iterator Category | Capabilities | Containers |
|-------------------|-------------|------------|
| Input | Read forward | `istream_iterator` |
| Output | Write forward | `ostream_iterator` |
| Forward | Read/write forward | `forward_list` |
| Bidirectional | Read/write both directions | `list`, `set`, `map` |
| Random Access | Full pointer-like access | `vector`, `deque`, `array` |

---

### Basic Usage

```cpp
vector<int> vec = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};

// Forward iteration
auto it = vec.begin();
while (it != vec.end()) {
  cout << *it << " ";
  ++it;
}

// Reverse iteration
auto rit = vec.rbegin();
while (rit != vec.rend()) {
  cout << *rit << " ";
  ++rit;
}
```

---

### Iterator Functions

| Function | Returns |
|----------|---------|
| `begin()` / `end()` | Iterator to first / past-last |
| `cbegin()` / `cend()` | Const iterator |
| `rbegin()` / `rend()` | Reverse iterator |
| `crbegin()` / `crend()` | Const reverse iterator |

---

### Modifying with Iterators

```cpp
vector<int> nums = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

for (auto it = nums.begin(); it != nums.end(); ++it) {
  *it *= 2;  // Double each element
}
```

---

> **Key Point:** Iterators behave like pointers. Use `*` to dereference and access the element, `++` to advance, and `--` for bidirectional iterators.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  vector<int> numbers = {100, 200, 300};

  cout << "Forward: ";
  for (auto it = numbers.begin(); it != numbers.end(); ++it) {
    cout << *it << " ";
  }

  cout << "\nReverse: ";
  for (auto it = numbers.rbegin(); it != numbers.rend(); ++it) {
    cout << *it << " ";
  }
  return 0;
}
